==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} ''[[lynspin]]'', compound of ''[[lins]]'' 'axletree' and ''[[pin]]'', from {{etyl|ang}} ''[[lynis]]'' 'linchpin', from {{proto|Germanic}} *''luniso'' (cf. {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Lünse}}), from {{proto|Indo-European}} (cf. {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|olwyn}} 'wheel', {{etyl|hy|-}} {{term|ołn}} 'shoulder', {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|āṇís}}). Figurative use attested from the mid-20th century.

===Alternative spellings===
* [[lynchpin]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# a pin inserted through holes at the end of an axle, so as to secure a wheel
# {{figurative}} a central [[cohesive]] source of [[stability]] and [[security]]; a person or thing that is critical to a system or organization.

